    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Paper 1 · Version 2 · June 2026
    </div>
    <h1>Stable Is Not Grounded — the hierarchy</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      One cut in a strict hierarchy, observable only as deep as both sides are transparent.
    </p>

    <h2>What changed from v1</h2>
    <p>
      v1 gave a non-circular procedure for deciding what counts as an irrelevant variable. v2 stops
      treating that as a standalone method beside an accuracy-vs-stability aside and folds both into a
      single object: a strict three-level hierarchy, with the non-circular cut as its deepest level.
    </p>

    <h2>The hierarchy</h2>
    <p>
      Headline accuracy merges three behaviours that come apart under answer-preserving perturbation —
      unstable, stable-wrong, stable-correct — and checking stability separates only the first. The
      residual is reflexive: a stable-correct answer can hold because the model tracks the licensing
      structure, or because it stably rides a shortcut that also correlates with the answer.
    </p>
    <blockquote>accuracy ⊋ stability ⊋ grounding — every containment non-empty.</blockquote>
    <p>
      Stability is necessary but not sufficient for grounding.
    </p>

    <h2>The decidability boundary</h2>
    <p>
      The deepest cut, <code>SC → {"{grounded, spurious}"}</code>, requires
      <strong>two-sided observability</strong>: the item's ground-truth graph must be stipulated by
      construction (benchmark-side), and the candidate shortcut's training correlation must be
      auditable (model-side). When both sides are open the cut is decidable; when either goes dark it
      is non-identifiable from the available observations, and the honest decomposition stops at the
      stable / stable-wrong split.
    </p>
    <p>
      A <code>do</code>-intervention that severs a variable satisfying both halves, paired with the
      mandatory pure-noise control, decides grounded vs spurious without reintroducing circularity.
    </p>

    <h2>The sharp consequence</h2>
    <p>
      A stably-correct-but-spurious model and a stably-wrong-by-shortcut model are the
      <em>same mechanism</em>, split only by evaluation luck — so even the stable-correct /
      stable-wrong boundary is eval-contingent until the deepest cut is made. On two model classes the
      same headline accuracy and near-identical stability decompose into opposite grounding verdicts;
      the verdict reproduces on a third architecture (Qwen-LoRA) and ports to a never-fine-tuned
      reasoner that ignores even a perfect in-context shortcut. HANS is read as a syntactic-heuristic
      instance of the same cut.
    </p>

    <h2>Why it became the workshop reshape</h2>
    <p>
      v2's own §7 conceded a gap: it lacked a natural <code>SC-grounded</code> witness, because a
      single-language shortcut benchmark cannot supply one. The fix was already implicit — grammar
      stipulates which structure licenses an inference and which surface cue is irrelevant — so the
      next step re-anchored the paper to linguistic structure and added a cross-lingual agreement
      witness.
    </p>

